          "title": "Strife, quarrels, and the flood that cannot be recalled (17:1, 9, 14, 19)",
          "body": "Three separate verses treat strife as an active destructive force rather than a passive relational problem. The household feasting poisoned by strife (17:1), the friend-separator who repeats a matter (17:9), and the one who loves transgression and loves strife as its companion (17:19) all build toward the chapter's most powerful metaphor: *the beginning of strife is like letting out water* (17:14). The Hebrew *patar* (to release, let go, burst out) is the word for breaching a dam or breaking open a sealed vessel. Once water has been released, it cannot be recalled. The pastoral application is precise and urgent: *abandon the quarrel before it breaks out* — the one imperative in the chapter, and it has a deadline. The Talmud (b. Sanhedrin 7a) reflects on this proverb, observing that judges must resolve disputes at their earliest stage; once litigation has been released it is like the sea. The canonical wisdom is consistent: James 4:1 traces wars and quarrels to internal desires; Proverbs 17:14 traces them to an external moment of release that is preventable only before it occurs."
